## Implementation Notes

The fix replaces two non-idiomatic collection-emptiness checks in `src/deliver/send_proxy.cr` with the Crystal-standard `.empty?` pattern. The change is two lines, no logic is altered.

**What I built:** A style-only correction. No new methods, classes, or test cases were added.

**Challenges faced:** None. The fix was straightforward once the correct form for each line was determined (see reasoning below under Approach decisions).

### Code Changes

- **Files modified:** `src/deliver/send_proxy.cr`
- **Key commits:** [Links will be added after pushing to fork]
- **Approach decisions:**
  - **Line 16** — `if endpoint.params.size > 0` → `unless endpoint.params.empty?`
    The original `if` block has an `else` branch, but it controls the entire body of the spawned fiber, so reading it as "unless params are empty, do the parameterized request" is natural and matches the dominant form used in output builders and engines throughout the codebase.
  - **Line 19** — `body = if endpoint_hash["json"].size > 0` → `body = if !endpoint_hash["json"].empty?`
    This is an inline `if/else` expression used on the right-hand side of an assignment. Using `unless ... else` in this form is considered poor style in Crystal (the logic inverts twice and reads confusingly), so `!.empty?` is the correct choice here, consistent with how compound/inline conditions are written elsewhere in the codebase (e.g., `cli_validation.cr`, `detector.cr`).

